# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: andreas-schockenhoff
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/achim-großmann] After graduating from high school in 1966 at the Kaiser-Karls-Gymnasium in Aachen, Großmann studied psychology at the TH Aachen, which he completed in 1972 with a diploma in psychology.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/achim-großmann] He then worked as an educational consultant at the advice center for parents, children and young people in Alsdorf until 1986, and as its director since 1979.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/achim-großmann] At the same time, he worked for several semesters as a lecturer in administrative psychology at the University of Applied Sciences for Public Administration in Aachen.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/achim-großmann] Achim Großmann was divorced and had two children.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/achim-großmann] From 1975 to 1998, Großmann was a councilor for the city of Würselen.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/achim-großmann] After the 1998 federal election, he was appointed Parliamentary State Secretary to the Federal Minister for Transport, Construction and Housing in the Government led by Gerhard Schröder.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/achim-großmann] After the formation of the Grand Coalition under Chancellor Angela Merkel, the ministry was renamed the Federal Ministry of Transport, Building and Urban Development.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/achim-großmann] After the 2009 federal election and the subsequent change in government, Großmann left office in October 2009.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/achim-großmann] In his eleven years in office, he served under five different construction and transport ministers.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/achim-großmann] As Parliamentary State Secretary, Achim Großmann was a member of the supervisory board of Deutsche Bahn and was involved in the preparations for the IPO.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/achim-post] Post became a member of the Bundestag in the 2013 German federal election.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/achim-post] In parliament, he was a member of the Joint Committee.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/achim-post] From 2015 to 2023, Post led the Bundestag group of SPD parliamentarians from North Rhine-Westphalia, the largest delegation within the party's parliamentary group.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/achim-post] From 2017, he served as one his parliamentary group's chairpersons, under the leadership of successive chairs Andrea Nahles (2017–2018) and Rolf Mützenich (2018–2025).
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/achim-post] In addition to his committee assignments, Post was part of the German-Egyptian Parliamentary Friendship Group.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/achim-post] In September 2024, Post announced that he would not stand in the 2025 federal elections but instead resign from active politics by the end of the parliamentary term.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/adelheid-d-tröscher] She attended grammar school and high school in Ithaca, New York, United States, graduating in 1959.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/adelheid-d-tröscher] She then studied education, history and English language and literature in Marburg, Jugenheim an der Bergstraße and Frankfurt am Main and passed her first and second state examinations to become a teacher at secondary schools.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/adelheid-d-tröscher] In 1962 she was accepted into the teaching profession and from 1975 to 1976 she worked in the school department of the Regierungspräsidium Darmstadt.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/adelheid-d-tröscher] From 1986 to 1992, she was head of the Paul Hindemith Comprehensive School in Frankfurt am Main.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/adelheid-d-tröscher] After leaving the parliamentary group in the Bundestag of her own accord, she became involved in the SPD on a voluntary basis, particularly in the *Forum One World*, which deals with development policy issues.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/adelheid-d-tröscher] She also heads the Rhine-Main regional group of Transparency International.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/adelheid-d-tröscher] She is also involved as chairwoman of the Citoyen Foundation, which supports civic engagement and is particularly concerned with the artistic and aesthetic education of children and young people.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/adelheid-d-tröscher] Tröscher is the daughter of Tassilo Tröscher.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/adelheid-d-tröscher] From 1972 to 1977, from 1981 to 1989 and in 1991 she was a city councillor of the city of Frankfurt am Main, and from 1992 to 1993 a full-time district councillor of the Kreis Offenbach.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/adelheid-d-tröscher] From November 1994 to October 2002, Tröscher was a member of the German Bundestag for two terms.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/adelheid-d-tröscher] In the 1994 Bundestag election, she entered parliament via the SPD state list, and in the 1998 Bundestag election she won the direct mandate in the constituency 144 (Odenwald).
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/adelheid-d-tröscher] From 1994 to 2002, she was a member of the Committee on Economic Cooperation and Development and from 1996 to 2002, she was the SPD parliamentary group's spokesperson on development policy.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/adelheid-d-tröscher] Tröscher is a member of GEW, AWO, Kinderschutzbund, Pro Familia and medico international.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/adelheid-d-tröscher] In 1999 she became a member of the board of trustees and the administrative committee of Deutsche Stiftung für internationale Entwicklung (DSE) and a member of German Foundation for International Development.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/adelheid-d-tröscher] (DSE) and a member of German Agro Action.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-alpers] Starting in 1980, Alpers studied pedagogy at the Free University of Berlin, finishing her Diplom degree in 1986.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-alpers] Subsequently, she was active in child welfare.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-alpers] She is a founder of school groups and was the leader of the first Kids Samba Group in Bremen during Carnival.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-alpers] After a speech in the Bundestag on 28 June 2013, Alpers collapsed and had to be resuscitated on site.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-alpers] A stroke as a result of an aneurysm was diagnosed, and Alpers was placed into an artificial coma.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-alpers] By the end of July, she was taken out of her coma.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-alpers] In September, she was moved to a hospital in Bremen and is currently undergoing rehabilitation.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-alpers] She handed in her Bundestag mandate effective 2 March 2015 and was succeeded in office by Birgit Menz.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-alpers] Agnes Alpers was a member of the "Socialist Unity Party of West Berlin", which was closely related to the Socialist Unity Party of Germany and the German Communist Party in West Berlin.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-alpers] From October 2007, Alpers represented the Left in a Bremen "Deputation" (a kind of local parliamentary council) for Education in the Bremen Parliament.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-alpers] In September 2009, she was elected to the Bundestag (or German Parliament) as part of the Bremen state party list.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-alpers] In parliament, she is a member of the Committee on Education, Research, and Technology.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-alpers] Despite her stroke, Alpers remained the lead candidate on the Bremen state party list and was reelected to the Bundestag in the federal election in 2013.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-alpers] Alpers supported a cross-party bill, brought to parliament by a group of over 50 representatives on 8 November 2012, which would limit circumcision for religious purposes for only those who have reached religious maturity (14 years).
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-krumwiede] Krumwiede is a pianist and a qualified musician with a concert exam.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-krumwiede] She ran a piano school in Ingolstadt until 2009 and worked as a freelance concert pianist and song accompanist.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-krumwiede] She also worked as a freelancer for Bayerischer Rundfunk and Donaukurier.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-krumwiede] Krumwiede is single, lives in Ingolstadt and has a son with politician Stephan Kühn.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-krumwiede] Her sister Franziska Krumwiede-Steiner is also a Member of the German Bundestag.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-krumwiede] Krumwiede has been a member of the Greens party since 2001.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-krumwiede] She is a founding member of the Green Youth in Ingolstadt and was a scholarship holder of the party-affiliated Heinrich Böll Foundation during her studies.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-krumwiede] In 2002 and 2008, she ran for the city council in Ingolstadt and in 2003 she was a candidate for the state list in the Bavarian state elections.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-krumwiede] In the 2009 Bundestag election she ran as a direct candidate in the Ingolstadt constituency and received 8.2% of the first votes.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-krumwiede] She was elected into the Bundestag via Landeslistenplatz 9.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-krumwiede] There, she was spokeswoman for cultural policy of the parliamentary group of the Greens and chairwoman of the parliamentary group in the committee for culture and media.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-krumwiede] Krumwiede lost her seat in the 2013 federal election, thus missing re-entry into parliament.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnes-krumwiede] In Nancy Brandt's film "The Elected", Krumwiede was one of five young MPs who were accompanied in a long-term film study during their first legislative period from 2009 to 2013.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnieszka-brugger] Born in Legnica, Poland, Brugger moved to West Germany with her parents in 1989.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnieszka-brugger] She grew up in Dortmund, where she graduated from the Mallinckrodt-Gymnasium, a private highschool operated by the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Paderborn.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnieszka-brugger] She studied political science at the University of Tübingen, so far without graduation, as she interrupted her academic studies for her political career.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnieszka-brugger] From 2005 until 2007, Brugger was a member of the General Students' Committee (AStA) of the University of Tübingen.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnieszka-brugger] She later led the Green Youth in Baden-Württemberg between 2007 and 2009.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnieszka-brugger] Brugger has been a member of the German Bundestag since the 2009 election.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnieszka-brugger] From 2013 until 2017 she served as her parliamentary group's spokeswoman on the Defense Committee and the Subcommittee on Disarmament, Arms Control and Non-Proliferation.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnieszka-brugger] In her capacity as member of the Defense Committee, Brugger has traveled extensively to visit Bundeswehr troops on their missions abroad, including the United Nations Multidimensional Integrated Stabilization Mission in Mali (2015) and the Operation Counter Daesh at the Incirlik Air Base (2016).
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnieszka-brugger] In early 2018, she became part of her parliamentary group’s leadership around co-chairs Katrin Göring-Eckardt and Anton Hofreiter.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnieszka-brugger] In this capacity, she oversees the group's initiatives on foreign affairs, defense and development policy.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnieszka-brugger] In 2018 she was elected vice-chair of Alliance ‘90/The Greens in Bundestag, responsible for coordination of the caucus on the issues of Foreign Affairs, Defense, Human Rights, Development and European Affairs.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnieszka-brugger] She has been reelected to this position in 2021 and 2025.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnieszka-brugger] In 2023, Brugger was one of the initiators – alongside Michelle Müntefering and Marie-Agnes Strack-Zimmermann – of a cross-party group promoting a feminist foreign policy.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnieszka-brugger] After the Russian invasion of Ukraine, Brugger was a strong advocate for solidarity with Ukraine, including the shipments of weapons to Ukraine and strong sanctions against Russia.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnieszka-brugger] On Libya, Sudan, South Sudan and Somalia, Brugger has a mixed voting record.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnieszka-brugger] She opposes German participation in EU Navfor Med.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnieszka-brugger] She abstained from the votes on the missions for Darfur/Sudan (2017) and South Sudan (2017) after previously voting in favor of both missions (2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014 and 2015).
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnieszka-brugger] Since 2009, she has regularly abstained from votes on extending the mandate for the mission of Operation Atalanta.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/agnieszka-brugger] She also abstained (2015) or voted against German participation in the EUTM Somalia (2016 and 2017).
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/albert-dess] Albert Dess graduated from Agricultural college in 1966.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/albert-dess] He obtained his Master's in agriculture in 1979.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/albert-dess] Albert had a Secondary occupation as farmer and worked in commerce and industry.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/albert-dess] He became managing director of a farming cooperative and in 1977, a Full-time farmer/training establishment.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/albert-dess] In 1974 Albert Dess became the District Chairman of the Junge Union.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/albert-dess] In 1981 he became a Member of the CSU district executive and later in 1984, he became the Municipal Chairman of the CSU.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/albert-dess] He later rose in ranks by becoming the District Chairman in 1987, Regional Vice-chairman (1989–1995) and Regional Chairman (1995) of the CSU Agricultural Association.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/albert-dess] Albert was a Member of the CSU district executive from 1989 and in 1997, a member of the CSU Regional Executive Committee.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/albert-dess] From 1972 to 1996 he was in the Municipal Councillor, Berngau.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/albert-dess] He became a District Councillor, Neumarkt/Oberpfalz in 1978.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/albert-dess] In 1984–1996, he was the Vice-chairman of Neumarkt/Oberpfalz district council and from 1984 to 1996, the Mayor of Berngau.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/albert-dess] Albert Dess from 1992 to 2004 was the Farm policy spokesman for the CSU Regional Group in the Bundestag and from 1997 to 2004, a Member of the CDU/CSU Group Executive Committee.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/albert-dess] He later became the Chairman of the CSU Regional Group working party for Agriculture, Consumer Protection, Environment, Transport, Building and Energy from 2000 to 2004.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/albert-dess] Dess was a member of the European Parliament's Committee on Agriculture and Rural Development (AGRI).
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/albert-dess] He was a substitute for the Committee on International Trade (INTRA), a member of the delegation for relations with Mercosur and a substitute for the delegation to the ACP-EU Joint Parliamentary Assembly.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/albert-dess] In May 2018, Dess announced that he would not stand in the 2019 European elections but instead resign from active politics by the end of the parliamentary term.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/albert-dess] Outside Germany, Dess is best known for trying to introduce in the European Parliament a Volkswagen-written piece of legislation that would have exempted a whole class of vehicle from pollution controls.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/albert-dess] The proposal was dropped after the Volkswagen emissions violation scandal erupted and Dress has thus far refused requests to comment on his actions.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/andreas-schockenhoff] From 2006 until early 2014, Schockenhoff served as coordinator for the Cabinet of Germany, and was responsible for German-Russian cooperation.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/andreas-schockenhoff] As distinctive foreign policymaker he was known for his criticism of Vladimir Putin's government, and supported a more active German role in international crises.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/andreas-schockenhoff] He announced in 2011 that he was undergoing therapy for his alcohol addiction.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/andreas-schockenhoff] Schockenhoff was born in Ludwigsburg, Germany.
[src:andreas-schockenhoff/andreas-schockenhoff] He died in Ravensburg, Germany, aged 57 from either heart failure or heat exposure after entering a sauna.
